    "visualization_explanation": "The visualization uses a polar coordinate system to represent social relationships through angular positioning and radial distance encoding. Nodes (\u03bc=5 connections, \u03c3=2.1) show power-law distribution typical in social networks. The networkgraph series type maintains Tufte's data-ink ratio by eliminating redundant axes while using position (angle = group affiliation, radius = connection count) and color (gender coding) as primary channels. Cairo's principles are applied through: 1) Pre-attentive color coding (blue=male, red=female) 2) Connection opacity encoding relationship strength 3) Polar symmetry for pattern recognition. Synthetic data maintains domain validity through realistic connection counts (max 4, min 1) and gender distribution (25% male). Plot bands create concentric perceptual anchors while reversed radial axis positions core members centrally."
